Parliament does not support the amendment giving freedom to Tymoshenko
Today, in the course of the amendments to the Criminal Procedure Code, the Parliament of Ukraine rejected an attempt to repeal an article according to which the opposition leader, Yulia Tymoshenko, was convicted.
The amendment, which would have led to the release of the former prime minister in prison, was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on the easing of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia that was deemed unprofitable.
The verdict is not yet final; the court will consider Tymoshenko’s appeal in December.
Tymoshenko claims that the sentence is a political vendetta of the regime; in the West, the trial was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal Article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, according to which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 Members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes to be ratified.
