Ambassador to the EU VICENOVA:
The Czechs have a reputation of malcontents and skeptics towards the euro.
"The Lisbon Treaty has caused considerable disagreements between individual organisations."
“I didn’t expect such a brutal war.”
“It will take five or six years before the situation stabilizes, calms down and all players get used to their new roles,” EU Ambassador Milena Vicenova began her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
She proved how much she adheres to her “Clearly and openly about Europe” motto in the first part of her lecture, where she described individual EU institutions and the relationship between them so simple and understandable that many lecturers from the Faculty of Law of the University of Kyiv would envy.
Moreover, Vicenova praised the work of the new permanent president of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
“At first, critics said he was an ordinary gray office mouse who couldn’t perform any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he handled his role.”
“He is a person who can listen to twenty-seven countries at the same time, communicate with them perfectly and who has a clear idea of which direction the EU needs to develop.”
She explained her new position as a representative for international relations and security issues as an answer to the question: "Who is the European Union? What number should I call?"; i.e. as an important step towards unification and greater transparency of the Union's policies towards countries such as China or India.
No one is going to ban our cheeses.
Vicenova went on to focus on a programme that is key to the EU in the past, present and the near future.
She called the Czech Republic’s presidency successful last year.
The Czechs were dealing with an impending financial crisis; they overcame this crisis and organized an Eastern Partnership summit.
She said that the resignation of the government at the time was a negative phenomenon, causing considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
At present, the Czech representatives in the EU are very busy.
As the Ambassador said, both the Presidency and the subsequent financial crisis have caused the ongoing turmoil.
In addition, it is necessary to adopt a new seven-year EU budget, which is very difficult, given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be scarce and economical, which areas will be preferred; which countries will receive more support, and which will receive less; all these issues are in the forthcoming programme.
The ambassador recalled the key slogans she had brought to Brussels: "About Europe, in understandable language".
“I really don’t like abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that no one understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curves or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our cheese varieties?
It is also going to make more efficient use of the EU environment and attract more Czechs to European organisations.
Multi-speed Europe is our future
The ambassador claims that the Czechs are considered Euro-skeptics; as well as people who note the negative rather than the positive sides of things.
She wants more Czech representatives to be involved in European organisations.
She believes that this is due to several factors: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivational letters; at the same time, with little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful Czech Presidency, she noted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland and Hungary, and a Slovak joins us, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, what's the meeting about, the Visegrad Group again?' and he's not happy about it.'
In the future, the Union of Vicenov expects mainly new strict rules for the budgetary policies of the states parties.
Compared to the new European Federation, it considers the idea of a two-speed, if not multi-speed, Europe more realistic.
“We have countries both inside and outside the Eurozone.”
“We have the Schengen area, and we already have an institution of enhanced cooperation.”
“For the first time, it was said that countries that want to unite, while those that don’t can stay on the sidelines.”
“The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe,” Vicenova expects.
In this regard, she stressed the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in advancing the rule that all EU-wide issues should be discussed by all member countries, not just those in the Eurozone.
History of the brand:
The IBM innovator enters the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find the word that best expresses the IMB strategy, the closest one is likely to be “long-term.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The company's longevity was established by its first boss, dreamer Thomas J. Watson, Sr.
He believed in his motto that many world problems can be easily solved if people want to think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the life of the future giant revolved (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson carefully built.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means a constant movement toward the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, though not afraid to change everything around it.
For the first 100 years, this has allowed us to transform technology, business and company.
For the second hundred years, we hope to achieve even more,” says Samuel J. Palmizano, the company’s current CEO on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complicated system
