Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Are Studying You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Breivik was an ordinary guy who exposed his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to a mass murder in Norway in July that claimed the lives of 77 people, appeared at his first open court hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was far from alone on the net: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
It's easy - just go to Facebook.
“We’ve come to understand that it’s not difficult to access them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European cyber-populism by the British Research Centre DEMOS.
The stock of personal data on Facebook is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site’s advertising tool to single out the necessary demographic group with scientific accuracy — which marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then pushed ads to them, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ad asked the user to go through a survey that included questions about their level of education, attitudes to violence, and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to poll more than 10,000 participants from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – even without leaving the office.
“This is a completely new way to conduct research,” says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are dissatisfied with immigration.
But unexpectedly, “those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more reasonable, more democratic, and less aggressive than those who are just hiding behind a monitor.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything in the world – from health issues to social trends, which are expressed in ‘Likes’, posts on the wall and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts a day, Facebook’s “super-actual information” is causing a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the site’s title by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it makes it possible to study people who cannot be approached on the street with a notebook.
“In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them.”
“You would have to join the party, and they would never have accepted you,” Bartlett says.
“Facebook excludes all of this – you’re addressing them directly.”
Others say that this site could be used to identify and investigate social health issues.
