“We found a way to identify children from a risk group that we wouldn’t otherwise have found.”
Facebook is also constantly extracting different kinds of data about its users.
The site’s data processing team processed statistics on Valentine’s Day and relationship statuses, mid-term turnout in 2010, as well as the National Happiness Index (mainly using information that only they have access to – cyber-freedom champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive collection).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for the ability to play Scrabby with a friend thousands of miles away from you, the site can process your personal data.
But what about when Facebook users become participants in a study they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict rules for conducting offline research, online data is publicly available.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about what a researcher can look at their profiles,” says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a study he conducted in 2006 using students’ public pages on Facebook.
“As far as they imagined, it was only between them and their friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that the subject of the study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much information in the profile and on the user's page is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” says Selvin.
That’s why, despite years of work in technology research, Selvin thinks that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools you can use.
“Nothing can replace going out into the real world and communicating with real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about social, and most of the social is still going offline.”
