7 Lessons From Steve Jobs’s Lost Interview Shown at the Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans might consider the biggest discovery in the recently-discovered interview, which they recalled ahead of previews in major markets this week, is how much that creative mind understood in business processes and manufacturing technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a diligent organizer and modernizer of the production process, who believed that many business leaders suffered from “the disease of thinking that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work...[but] a great idea from a great product takes a huge amount of effort.”
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created the TV series Triumph of the Nerds about the advent of a personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a unique long conversation.
It’s been about 10 years since Jobs was kicked out of Apple, and he’s already been working at his new NeXT computer company waiting for the Internet to take off.
While a small part of Kringley’s interview was used in Nerds, he says the original interviews were missing during transportation.
It was only after Jobs’s death that a full VHS copy was found in the director’s garage.
This footage, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which comes out at Landmark Theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of detailed interviews, Jobs seems unusually willing to lay out his technological philosophy and business strategy here.
And incredibly thoughtful.
At four different points during the interview, there are large intervals between questions and answers—thinking for 10-15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to say more accurately.
There are also times when Job’s perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems irritated by Kringle’s questions, forcing him to move faster to more important issues or phenomena.
In the pre-Pixar era, there’s something ominously prophetic about the Lost Interview, when Jobs assesses what he sees different companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision for the future of information technology.
It’s one thing to read about Jobs’ post-mortem evaluations of his work, but there’s something hurtful and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, a disturbing dreamer on the threshold of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Soon after he said everything here, he went and did it.
A brief summary of the seven significant conclusions of the Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
“All the time in business, I’ve been constantly asking, ‘Why are you doing this?’ and the answers you invariably get, ‘Oh, that’s just how it’s done.’
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks in business very deeply.
Here's what I found out.
Jobs continues to detail his efforts to streamline reporting at Apple.
Disturbed by the way expenses were recorded, often starting with “standard expenses” that were taken from the ceiling and then adjusted by “accuracy,” he created an automated structure that ensured that they could track business expenses down to the smallest.
A joke about the Pope:
Jobs details the “blue box” he mastered with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device before, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the blue box as an act of empowering is contagious.
He recounts how he and Wozniak tested the box using an automated phone, ordering a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until they connected as many stations as possible.
“We’ve covered the globe half a dozen times, and you’ve been yelling at the phone machine, and it was penetrating the neighboring phone machine a minute later,” Jobs says with a smile.
“We were young, and all we learned was that we could master something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us knew a little bit, but we could master a little thing that could control a big thing — it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think without it Apple could ever have come along.
Jobs goes on to describe in detail one famous outing that he and Wozniak practically handled by calling the Vatican via a blue box at midnight and asking for a phone call from the Pope, struggling to copy Henry Kissinger.
When various members of the Catholic hierarchy were called in the middle of the night to speak to an American diplomat, the two burst out laughing just before the Pope himself was raised to answer the phone.
About the love of technology (and Bill Hullett’s cold name):
At the age of 12, while searching for spare parts to assemble the frequency meter, he found Bill Hullett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a summer job at Hullett Parkard.
“It had a strong impact on me, it was the only company I’d seen at that age, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the very first desktop computer.”
He was the size of a suitcase, he had a small monitor with an electron beam tube, and I fell in love with him.
I used to go to HP as a teenager and spin around that car and write programs for it.
On Improvised Innovation:
In several places, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
At the dawn of his career, when he went to sell a handful of mounting plates, one buyer asked him to assemble an entire computer.
Working only 30 days on the loan, he had to think about both the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he recalls the difficulties he faced when developing a computer mouse:
“I remember furious arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to collect a mouse that would cost $300] and I was fed up with it and came out and found a designer.”
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we were able to collect for $15, which was incredibly reliable.
Some of the companies that are losing energy:
Long before he led Apple’s revival, Jobs accurately predicted how many industry leaders would be wrong in their vision of the situation and lose control of their market share.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make the best copy or printer, and what?”
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company does not become more successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are the types of people] who ultimately come to run the companies, and the people making the product are being pushed out of the decision-making platform.
The genius of the product that led to this monopolistic position is supplanted by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products – the required skill.
This is what happened to Xerox.
Xerox could take over the entire information technology industry.
It could have been ten times bigger, it could have been Microsoft in the '90s.
They were defeated by victory.
Innovation as a Form of Art:
“A great idea separates a huge amount of skilled work from a great product ... when you spin a great idea, it changes and grows.”
You will learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises you need to make – some things you won’t be able to make make electrons, glass, robots, or factories.
You need to keep 5,000 ideas in your head – these concepts – connecting them all together.
Ultimately, it all comes down to taste – it comes down to trying to express yourself in the best way that people have ever produced, and later – trying to bring it into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have always been ashamed to steal great ideas.
Part of what made McIntosh famous was that the people who worked on him were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to become the best specialists in the field of information technology in the world.
If it weren’t for information technology, they’d be doing amazing things in other areas.
