How to Catch a Lie
A cursory look at the latest headlines shows how serious and pervasive deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Caine is busy challenging allegations of sexual harassment from several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
The University of Pennsylvania administration has been charged with falsification because they allegedly concealed the fact that a retired football coach had raped the boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar when he turned on the microphone.
Lying destroys careers and shakes countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner has made a fool of himself by denying his findings, which has quickly been refuted by undisputed evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with financial fraud during a campaign related to the cover-up of extramarital affairs.
And again, none of those who lived at that time will ever forget the media circus with President Bill Clinton, insinuated in lies about his sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of fraud on exams at school and college are commonplace.
There have been cases where teachers have given students answers to tests in order to have a good assessment of the results of their activities.
The mentors who have to teach the opposite send a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many lies do we face?
In one day, studies show, you can lie 10 to 200 times.
Now it is assumed that a significant part of this is lies in salvation.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of dating each other.
Identifying a lie or exposing a lie is a skill that everyone needs for both personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room game, similar to, say, charades, where you need to yell “Found!”, the detection of lies is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lies have been debunked.
The liars look into their eyes.
They don’t always get stuck, stuttered, reddened, or dizzy.
It is not necessary to conclude from this that liars are difficult to notice and difficult to expose.
An experienced liar can get to the truth by observing the structure of statements, mimicry, question structure, and temporal characteristics.
I’ve spent several years researching scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of knowledge about lies, and it’s clear that detecting lies is a modern skill that’s easy to learn and that helps guide in our complex world — especially if your professional responsibilities include managing, negotiating, or negotiating.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel relaxed, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from the study that extroverts are more likely to lie than introverts, that men are more likely to lie about themselves, while women are more likely to lie about others, usually to protect someone else’s feelings, that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than unmarried people (but the lie they tell is most likely outright).
We also know that if you are perceived as a deceiver, others will feel less guilty about deceiving you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First of all, observe the normal behavior of your object.
This is called the “determining of the original state.”
This helps to provide a starting point for evaluating the changes further.
Observe the posture, laughter, voice characteristics of your object.
It would be good for you to know if a person is constantly knocking on his feet in a normal state, then you will not be making unfair accusations when you see the knocking on his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for a group of deceptive verbal and nonverbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Cheaters can fix the upper part of their body when they try to remember their story, they can put their feet in the direction of the door, lean toward the exit, change their posture in a certain way, or demonstrate "relief after an interview" -- this exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture when everyone is in a difficult situation.
Investigators often falsify the end-of-interview signal to simply look at this relief after an interview.
So, pay attention to the speech of your object.
It is known that Scott Peterson has backtracked and used the past tense, claiming that his murdered wife is alive, which led to her searches across the country.
Vaccinated people can also use distance in speech: “I did not have sexual relations with this woman ... Miss Lewinsky” or repeat the complex question completely.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely catchy.
Someone can use “qualification language” when answering a difficult question: “Well ... in truth ... as far as I know ... as far as I know.”
This makes the answer more emotional than factual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magic tool to detect lies, but you can master the skill of detecting deception.
These skills will increase everyone’s chances of not falling victim to skilled crooks in their professional and personal lives.
