A few days after the Obama administration threatened to postpone approval of the planned oil pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico -- provoking anger from trade unions, but calming environmentalists -- the company that is going to build the oil pipeline says it is willing to rework the project.
TransCanada said on Monday evening it would remove the planned pipeline from the environmentally sensitive Sand Hills area of Nebraska and is confident the project will still receive approval.
The company voiced this decision at a press conference in the Nebraska State Capitol.
TransCanada spokesman Alex Purbas says the company remains confident that it will eventually get approval for the pipeline, albeit with a different route.
This comes after the State Department said last week that it would postpone a decision on the project at the federal level until it explores new possible routes that do not affect the area of the Nebraska Sand Hills and the Ogallala aquifer, a huge underground water reservoir.
“This is a real step forward,” said Fox News congressman Lee Terry, a Republican from Nebraska.
A new environmental review ordered by the State Department is likely to reject the decision until 2013, after next year’s election, although authorities have denied that the decision involved policy.
In a written statement last week, Obama called the decision a State Department appeal and expressed support for it.
The 1,700-mile pipeline will run from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
He has to transfer 700,000 barrels a day from the province of Alberta to oil refineries in Texas.
To accomplish this, he needs to cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but it is loved by trade unions, who hope for about 20,000 oil pipeline-related jobs.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposing the plan are considering a bill to speed up the move from the Sand Hills area and the Ogallala aquifer, the main source of drinking water and irrigation.
The State Department’s current study on environmental impacts showed that the project would have only limited negative environmental impacts, but an energy industry source said the Department’s auditor had ordered a separate review of the review procedure, focusing on two issues.
One - whether the lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was an adviser to Hillary Clinton's campaign in 2008, represents a conflict of interest for the program.
The other was whether the choice of firm that was hired to conduct the initial study was inappropriate, as it was related to TransCanada.
