Climate change has slowed down the economy
During the first year of Mario Lopez’s rule in Sinaloa, unemployment and the illegal labor market increased, foreign funding decreased and the economy was weakened.
2011 - the year that will enter the economic history of Sinaloa as related to the first year of the government of Mario Lopez Valdes, also called the year of change, which gave rise to great hopes for the development of the economy, but given the unfavorable climatic conditions of the beginning of the year, there was no growth, however, there was a decrease in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February not only led to the losses of millions for the agricultural sector, but they limited the opportunities for the growth of the state economy, causing a decrease in economic activity by a total of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly due to the historical fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which is reflected in other sectors of the economy.
According to the report on areas affected by the frost provided by the Council of Mexico on the sustainable development of rural areas, 835,582 hectares were affected, of which 78.03 percent were affected in full, and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially affected. The main damaged crops were vegetables, corn and .
The decline in economic activity caused, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state with 18 per cent of the population, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, and during the first three quarters there was an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate, from January to March 55,053 residents of Sinaloa were unemployed, with an increase of 4.53 per cent, with an increase of 4.53 per cent.
Decreased liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is discussed by many factors, for economist Gerardo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, by actions that were taken in state policy.
“What we’re seeing right now is an increase in unemployment that is linked to several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market to limit the resources imposed by a law that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, as people who illegally own dollars are not easy to work with, invest in and use,” he said.
Abandoned immigration
Lopez Cervantes said that there is also a demographic factor in the growth of unemployment.
“The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad in the United States has been limited, firstly because of difficulties with entry, and secondly because, once entering, they already face a lot of difficulties in finding work, so a group of people stay in and require jobs here,” he said.
Violation of formal requirements
Sinaloa’s labor market analysis gets worse if you pay attention to the large number of violations that prevail in working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the state’s active population works without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and misdemeanors, another reminder of working in the state is low wages; the state has the lowest wages in the country, according to records from the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Ministry of Labor and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was up to September 5,352 pesos, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reduction of FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the high unemployment rate in 2011, the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the last 10 years was recorded, according to the Ministry of Finance, from January to July the state FDI amounted to 630,697 dollars.
For its part, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government recorded only 17,280,000 pesos of investments during the year, which mainly came from companies in the field of services.
Debt (disambiguation)
Against the backdrop of the economic downturn, the state government requested in July during the state congress the approval of a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2,600 million pesos were approved locally, and by November the benefits on debt were not expected to be shaken in any sector.
Responsibilities
For business representatives, the first year of the government of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdes demonstrates a lack of government capabilities.
Miguel Loredo Lopez, president of the National Chamber of Processing Industries, said that during 2011 there was a lack of coordination between the wishes of various sectors, including the state government itself.
“The efficiency of the economy in Sinaloa this year has been really low, it takes a lot of work to regain the positions lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we have not been able to coordinate the efforts of everyone and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that the next year will be better,” he said.
Deceleration of the economy
Lopez Loredo said that events such as the early freezes this year halted the state’s economy and its efficiency and growth were limited.
“Low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy that does not become fast enough to create an economic dynamic that allows for an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and, therefore, at the end of the year we close it below our expectations,” he said.
Revision of the direction
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that the state needs to continue the most dynamic production activity.
“Overall, we found that we were working on this, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, it is necessary to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
Upcoming work
President Coparmex stressed the importance of defining the future direction in order to better guide the government’s efforts.
“Overall, I would say that the government is trying to be successful in various areas, in terms of economic development there is little progress, but it is important to develop a long-term program,” he said.
He noted that the current administration had demonstrated progress in its own way of conducting public policy.
"There are facts that allow us to say that the government is starting to get involved and that I can say that some work has been done and, I think, the government is aware that there is much more to be done," he said.
