The court will approve the “transition to digital television” in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court rejected the constitutional claims put forward by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree, which postpones the so-called “digital TV transition” from 2021 to 2015, as no eight votes needed to cancel it have been cast.
A minority of the four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderon did not exceed his powers by issuing a decree detailing the steps to transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims filed by the Senate were rejected due to the lack of a qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of the radio and television program is a right enshrined in the law under the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted for the project.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the prime minister said he disagreed with the project’s arguments in the sense that the federal executive could not determine the general rules of the measures to be prepared by the state administration.
“I also don’t think that if this were to happen, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body,” he said, recalling that state policy planning in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is related to the federal executive branch, which has a constitutional mandate to govern the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that have occurred in recent years, leading to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of digital transformation, which includes meeting public needs that have not only a technical dimension, “as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he said, "require the work of the entire system, formed on the principle of state economic governance, includes a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into a state executive power."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and have done so with the help of the executive, despite the presence of highly specialized technical institutions.
From this it cannot be concluded that the government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the powers of Congress, ensures in the administrative sphere compliance with the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
