A new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present a new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the brink of an economic catastrophe.
Italian Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president on Wednesday to present a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of an economic catastrophe and damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he could form a government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive body will take its positions.
Monty said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to confirm my full confidence in our country’s ability to get out of this difficult period,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
“The structure is now well defined,” he said.
Monti completed the process of forming the government in less than three days, which is much less than usual, as Italy struggled with a political and financial crisis that brought the size of their debt to a critical level.
The administration under the leadership of former European Commissioner Monti must approve the austerity package required by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
Under pressure from Monti to hasten, volatile markets have set Italy’s BTP bond yield at more than 7 percent for 10 years, a level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marchegalia, the leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told reporters after a meeting with Monti: “We have said that we will actively support this government.”
We believe that this government is Italy’s last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monti's chances of success were largely based on the support of LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts should lead to a good outcome," Angelino Alfano, the center-right party's secretary, told reporters.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, matters because so far many of its members have opposed the government majority, consisting of technocrats, that forms Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support for reforms that are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspending of these attempts could lead to a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has stepped up pressure, warning that Monti’s failure could be a disaster.
Monty began his consultations Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women’s organizations.
He will finish his series of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, Italy’s debt value has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Italy’s bailout of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for the eurozone’s modern financial backers.
Monty said his government would exist until the next elections scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to reform before a new election is scheduled.
Monty said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the main parties insist that it should only be made up of technical experts, evidence of their dissatisfaction with the fact that the process is affected by the financial situation.
Political sources reported that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
