We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle, as far as these two things are concerned, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you find out about Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surf friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves here are incredible.
My friends always go surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, as well as Mexico, these are great places to surf, that’s how we learned about it, from people who love surfing.
Looking at the tour, you can say that you have made a great show with a lot of songs.
What did you plan to do in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there before, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible with a wide variety of songs; we will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce our fans to a wide variety of repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How does that work?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs, and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven’t played for a while, it keeps us in tune and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we could forget.
It makes the show more interesting to us and therefore, I think, makes it more interesting to people.
With this tour you celebrate 20 years of career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I think none of us could ever have imagined that we would be in a rock band and the fact that we’ve been doing this for over 20 years makes it look like a dream.
We are very happy with our luck and we are very excited that we can continue to create music together.
We all love each other and love making music.
We are happy to travel to places in the world where we have always wanted to go.
For us, everything is going very well.
What does it mean for you to be a significant part of the grunge bloom?
It has always been an honor to be part of this great team.
We are good friends with guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s great when the movement grows out of a group of friends, and it’s unusual.
From time to time, one group appears from one city, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups appear at the same time in the same city.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
I still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden during their tour, so we’re happy to be friends with all of them and it’s an honor for us to be part of the Seattle sound that came out.
It is also very strange that a group like yours stays together and in the same composition for so long.
Yes, four of us were together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than many bands exist.
First, I think we're lucky we're still alive, and second, we care about others.
We are all very close friends and, as a result, musical paths have also been opened that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other’s music, and everything could not have been better.
Your attitude to the word of glory was not easy; but thanks to your success you were able to do whatever you wanted.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became easier to find balance.
We take care not to be on tour too long because it’s easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for the sake of music, it reminds you that you have to respect music and what made it, not deciding to be famous and be a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
I think we write really good songs and in the beginning it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and didn’t release an album until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were a lot of disappointments because it took so long, and most importantly, we’re still close friends with Bruce (Ferveser) and Greg (Gilmore) who started with us in the band, and when I hear a song or see a photo, I think of the incredible person that Andy was, and he was, and I’ve always been.
He was a wonderful man and we miss him.
The local group Las Robertas will be responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you’re familiar with her work, especially Eddie Wedder, and that’s why you chose her to open up?
Yes, the producers sent us some video offers, and it was the band we liked the most, so we can’t wait to see what Las Robertas can offer live, and it should be very exciting.
Why do you constantly change the words in Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
It’s a question for Edu (Eddie Vedder), so I don’t know.
He sings it and, I think, he uses the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
There's so many of them.
Among the first to come to mind, Gizer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramon, John Dow, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukovsky ...
There are so many of them that I can talk all day about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in maintaining the relevance of grunge, despite the fact that it is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a bit detached from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of bands I’ve mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and everyone who came along at the same time, and if it’s important now, I think it’s great because it’s music that’s worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making music better now than ever.
At first your music was darker, and now it has become more positive.
How would you explain this change?
It’s interesting because I think there are a few songs on the album that may seem easier, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very dark, although they may sound a bit positive.
From both of them, when Ed played them, I cried when I listened to them, these songs are very dark.
I think that when you grow up and you’ve had some kind of trauma in your life and you’ve lost a family member or friend, these events begin to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to create dark music.
Peru:
Fuhimori was re-hospitalized for medical examination
Former President Alberto Fuhimori was hospitalized Tuesday at a state hospital to be examined for muscle strength loss that is seen in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fuhimori, 72, who was sentenced to 25 years in prison for human rights violations committed during his reign (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including cancer of the tongue, which has led to his being operated on four times and is under observation.
Congressman Alejandro Aginaga, who is his personal physician, told TV channel N that Fujimori would be examined in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of pain and loss of strength in his lower extremities.
Aginaga said that, in his opinion, Fuhimori should be a candidate for pardon for humanitarian reasons; however, he said he did not want it because he knew he was innocent.
He underwent four operations for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms, and other diseases, such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and problems with blood circulation in the legs, the doctor said.
Fuhimori has been in prison since September 2007, in the Police National Special Operations Directorate.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the army destruction squad, which acted in secret during the first years of his reign.
Mukhika goes to Mexico to strengthen political ties
The official delegation, led by Uruguay’s President Jose Mujica and consisting of several ministers and businessmen, will arrive in Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and start negotiations on the region’s political issues.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, the most important point of the extensive plan of meetings with political, commercial authorities and meetings with the community of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to a schedule published by the Uruguayan leadership.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will be "beneficial for the exchange of information on the issue of political relations between the two nations," the South American country's leadership said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderon’s support for Uruguay in an incident with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country in a list of tax havens at a G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay’s protest and withdrawal for consultations of his ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group made up of the most highly developed and developing countries, and has, essentially, an agreement with the South American country since January of this year on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the conclusion of tax-exchange agreements in order to leave this “grey list” of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, made up of countries that do not use international tax cooperation standards.
With regard to the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
The water pipe will be three-dimensional with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for more than 25 years to save Princess Pitch from the evil paws of the Bowser, but never before has he done so in three dimensions: in Super Mario 3D Land, he will fight for the love of a girl in stereoscopic technology.
