Minister Dionisio Perez Hakome talks about the details of the disaster, where the Minister of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven other people died.
The Ministry of Communications and Transport (MST) reported that the results of the accident, during which the Minister of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people died, showed that the helicopter struck directly on the ground in a state of complete integrity, without attempts to shoot the product.
During a press conference, Dionisio Perez Hakome, Minister of Communications and Transport, said that before the aircraft went up, the pilot found out that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The elements, which seem to show that the vessel had several contacts with the ground, the wings came into contact with the trees at 25 meters, where the means lost the flue gas."
He also reported that the ship was intended for 19 people, accordingly, it met the necessary requirements for the transportation of people.
He also said that studies conducted in the area of the impact did not report the presence of parts on the ground.
"The study reports that elsewhere there are no components of the ship, the impact occurred in a state of structural integrity.
“The helicopter was intended for 19 passengers, which met the relevant requirements of passenger transportation.
The earth in this place has an inclination of seven to 30 degrees.
By now, the secretary said, the main thing is to get the results as soon as possible; however, the study may take several months or even a year.
Meanwhile, Gilberto Lopez Meyer, CEO of Airports and Support Services, said that during the strike, the presidential helicopter was operated at cruising speed and that it happened on soft rising ground.
"This information reinforces the hypothesis of a normal flight maneuver at the time of impact," he said.
At a press conference, the owner of SCT, Peres Hakome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the rules of aviation, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, which means that the team must have visibility during the flight and landing.
Weather conditions:
The AICM reports identified suitable conditions for take-off when the aircraft headed for the border area between Mexico City and the State of Mexico, where cloud layers were observed at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is possible that due to cloud conditions, the team was looking for an area of lower elevation and greater visibility in the Cuernavaca Valley.
The location of the strike.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record from the radar of the aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or change of direction of flight.
Dispersion of debris in a small area:
The information available so far indicates that the impact occurred on the front and side lines.
The scattered debris makes it clear that the helicopter collided with the ground in conditions of structural integrity.
There were no obvious signs of fire or explosion:
In the area of the disaster remains undiscovered evidence in the wreckage of the ship, some kind of explosion or fire.
The results of the latest studies show that there could have been multiple contacts with the ground.
During work on the site were found pieces of the aircraft at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, the ground has a deviation from seven degrees to 30 degrees.
The pictures show the sequence in which it was destroyed along the way.
The information contains facts that seem to show that the helicopter may have had several collisions with the ground.
After careful study in a larger area than the delineated area near the crash site, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred under structural integrity conditions.
MSS Announces Obesity Gene Search Program
Social Protection Leads Research to Find Obesity Gene in Children and Young People; Supported by IPN Specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, which has been named the protocol “Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence”, which will provide a count of signs related to overweight.
In his statement, the head of the Division of Medical Research in Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the 21st century, Miguel Cruz Lopez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dieticians and social workers had been assembled.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students of the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (whether prescribed or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where every Saturday, from 8:00 a.m., children will be tested.
He stressed that the protocol began to be conducted at the sports center in Cuautemoc (in the west of the state of Mexico), and since October 8 events are held at the sports center in Nesaualcoyotl (east of the state of Mexico).
Once the goal of attracting 500 to 600 children is achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (southern Mexico) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (northern Mexico).
He explained that the purpose of this study was to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, and the main goal is to gather three thousand children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 years with the permission of their parents and under their supervision to fill out individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of family hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), measurement of blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) will be carried out.
Cruz Lopez said the study reflects health care professionals’ concerns about the alarming weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 indicate that there has been growth in just 6 years: in the case of boys, 77 percent were obese, in the case of girls, 47 percent; in terms of overweight, there has also been significant growth," the MSSI specialist said.
He said the rationale for searching for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population is different from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican is 65 percent descended from American Indians, 30 percent descended from Europeans, and five percent descended from Africans, and this condition has affected genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that basically, the result of obesity genetics is the body’s inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories), and it is deposited as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is a comprehensive assessment of the children, which can identify whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acanthas) and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with all confidentiality, the doctors transmit it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main reasons that provoke overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV and using transportation at short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to the high calorie consumption, that is, the increase in the consumption of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic predisposition analyzed in this program.
Asphalt UNAM can avoid cracks
Rafael Errera, a researcher at the UNAM chemical faculty, has developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a blend of the best quality, resistant to environmental and temperature impacts.
If the signals sent by the road surface were paid attention, it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the metropolitan area in the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM chemical faculty, and adds that if the construction and maintenance process can be completed with asphalt.
In his lecture Technological Look at Holes, read within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing a polymer-modified bitumen for the production of a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and therefore counteract the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of them high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscous behavior.
The viscous behavior of the bitumen is that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes brittle.
This means that the resistance of street asphalt is not constant, but varies throughout the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a specialist in chemical engineering.
A chemist noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which consists of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the uppermost layers is the bitumen, composed of small stones lowered into the bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is immersed in bitumen.
When moving vehicles and exerting effort, it helps the forces to distribute very well over the road surface.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would be distributed even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt coating, he added, is placed the last layer, which is called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, in fact sand also embedded in the asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will contact the transport wheels, it must have more resistance than the asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute these efforts, the wear layer also requires proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the state of the asphalt.
When the soil is raw, the water penetrates into the coating and it is difficult to get out of it, this causes the softening of all layers of the coating and, therefore, the formation of cavities.
In the formation of pits, he said, first wears out the wear layer and only then it affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur immediately, this process should be paid attention to at the first signs of current repair programs.
Also, a member of the National System of Researchers explained that the transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of the coating should always be associated with the transport load and it is necessary to guarantee compliance with this requirement to prevent frequent occurrence of pits.
Rafael Herrera said that concerning bitumen, much still needs to be studied and done, for example, bitumen emulsions that are already on the market in other countries and even help to fix pits with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
