This is one of the findings of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which was attended by six experts from different fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The Committee proposes that the Government amend the Criminal Code to allow for assisted suicide and euthanasia where that choice is made by circumstances and the patient can be considered competent to make such a decision.
To begin with, experts refer to a recent study by the Economic Bureau of Experts, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries of the world.
Although Canada ranks 10th, the study notes that “the medicalization of death in Canada has given birth to a culture in which people are afraid to argue about death.”
Medically or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts appointed by the Royal Society of Canada.
And 68.6% of them end up dead in the hospital.
The highest rate in the country is in Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in hospitals.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to a conclusion that contradicts the position of the federal government, which has already stated that it does not wish to change anything in the criminal code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Now, according to experts who have also studied the position of all countries where such actions have been legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, that is, the implementation of euthanasia or suicide with foreign aid against people who cannot or do not want to make such a decision.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downey, who presented the report, confirmed during the teleconference that the majority of such cases were in those countries where euthanasia and suicide with foreign aid were not legalized.
Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal.
Suicide with foreign aid is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal, explains Jocelyn Downey.
Canadians for Euthanasia
