As for the people who assisted in suicide, 41% of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
As for the extension or termination of medical care for patients, the situation is less clear, the authors of the report say.
They also propose, in addition to their other recommendations, that the criminal code should establish that legally legitimate termination of medical care is not a crime.
The Committee of Experts also requires that health professionals be trained in a spirit of respect for the abandonment of end-of-life medical care without fear of criminal prosecution.
With regard to palliative care, the Committee calls on the Government, health care institutions and doctors to work together to develop the best possible palliative care, and not just in cases of cancer.
Finally, with respect to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee requires that it be used when it is not used to dull physical pain, such as euthanasia, and is subject to the same restrictions.
