Energy Policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas.
If there is a topic on which a decision cannot be made after a short discussion or under the influence of emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election meetings become a reason to reflect on the share and place occupied by nuclear energy.
The dispute will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options have been explored.
France must build its opinion on objective facts and on rational data.
Now there are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic development will entail doubling the need for electricity by 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of vital elements.
During the same period, it will be necessary to fill the growing fossil resource deficit in order to continue producing electricity on an ongoing basis, not forgetting the critical need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate imbalance – a theme that has disappeared from environmental debates.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these factors.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case for Belgium, which makes its decision dependent on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear energy, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are just a few of those who are resolutely pursuing their projects.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add one installation to its kit, resuming construction of the station, which was interrupted after the accident on Three Mile Island.
Although the German model based on renewable energy is sometimes cited as an example, the reality contradicts this argument.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, increased energy dependence, aggravated by the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, the jump in carbon dioxide emissions in connection with the construction of gas and coal stations.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will already be felt.
Consider the example of Denmark.
The European champion in the construction of turbines, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, it is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to intermittent wind; due to which carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the average in Europe.
On the other hand, thanks to the permanence of our energy policy, our neighbors pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
In a globalized economy, the price of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and the key to servicing industrial equipment on national territory, and French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear energy will lead to a large increase in the cost of electricity, which will make illusory beautiful statements about the new industrialization of our country and the protection of purchasing power.
The price that most French refuse to pay, all the more so because they do not object to this type of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the country's energy policy has made it possible to create an industry of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a whole host of international trade-specialized small and medium-sized enterprises and creates many jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would have to sacrifice a large number of these enterprises and lose <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 million a year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrical engineer will order an EPR designed to run for sixty years if it is planned to shut down its manufacturer?
In order to solve the equation of energy, it must be recognized that there are no divine or diabolical sources of energy production.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest level of security for nuclear energy is undoubtedly a vital issue.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centres, such as Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is generally recognized, are full of the same obsession with security.
Over the past 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major incidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any consequences for humans or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the reactor device and the unforgivable human error led to a tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident occurred as a result of two natural disasters of unprecedented force that resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn lessons from this accident, as it learned from the two previous ones.
The fruit of this step and the cooperation between security authorities, operators and French and German designers, EPR, is a project that allows you to resist such phenomena.
As it is considered by all energy specialists who want to build a reactor, stopping its construction in Flamanville will be a great gift to competitors Areva and EDF, clearing the way for them to gain leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear energy.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and biased maneuvers to prevail in a dispute that is so important to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a benefit to the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized by various parties - the overload of police, judicial and administrative services subordinated to the policy of figures and the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a "state of human rights".
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which got into the news releases when the Minister of the Interior ("Liberasion" of May 23) declared that France "does not need foreign talents, stonemasons and waiters".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The right and the left agree on this issue in many ways.
On the right, Jacques Shirac declared in 1976 that “900,000 unemployed people will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers” and on the left, Michel Rocar, who explained in 1990 that France “cannot accept the poor from around the world”.
The only difference is the level of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of an invasion of the country by a Polish plumber was felt by both the left and the right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden for the French economy and for French society.
The difference is only in the level of generosity they will be willing to show to immigrants.
In his program Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande limited himself to banalities, saying that "joint work will solve our immigration problem."
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem can give an electoral advantage, but it is very expensive economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book that summed up the latest immigration data on immigration (Special People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Determine Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Publishing House, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among experts on immigration.
Restriction of immigration leads to a weakening of growth and reduces employment.
Fears of immigrants’ influence are based on the notion that they are capable of replacing local workers, especially the low-skilled, causing wage cuts.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are far more complementary than they are replacing the local labor force by doing jobs for which the local labor force is lacking.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract the local workforce, and the most skilled - in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
A positive impact on wages
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, the complementarity that exists between local and immigrant means that the arrival of immigrants has a positive impact on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in the migration flow leads to a 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
And this is without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (among American Nobel laureates a large share of naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo - all were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also make a net profit in social security systems, giving an average of 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
According to the World Labor Organization, for example, in Germany, an immigrant, arriving at the age of 30, will bring net income (income minus expenses) to the state budget for his life on average 150,000 euros.
Nicolas Sarkozy at the beginning of his mandate was going to "teeth" to cling to the missing growth points.
The mentioned teeth, which were used to scare away immigrants, gave the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it remains to understand European democracy
Democracy is a valuable acquisition; but at the same time it is fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it experienced the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some believed that for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it was enough to arrange a vote and make it as direct as possible.
Since the time of Napoleon the Little, it has been known that this comes from the superficiality of thought.
Universal suffrage, while an obligatory condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition and may even become an “instrument of repression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vashro once said.
No, democracy requires much else – public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of authorities, education, education, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but first and foremost it is a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this regard, the palinodism of the true and false Greek referendum will have a double revealing effect, demonstrating both the need for a serious change in policy and the unpleasant feeling of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality needs to be understood in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front line of the struggle for democracy has now shifted and, according to many, Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We will not win anything by demanding a series of national referendums, organized as necessary and in a chaotic manner.
"Cart Blanche" for an absolute European monarch or a jump with tied feet into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not dream of a guillotine blade, but of a joint, clear and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the pan-European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it is not known how many more will have to be listed, because there is only one crisis - the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is subject to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffers from its weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
Many are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but the whole of Europe is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The management of the European project must be restored to national sovereignty as a matter of urgency.
Because only by working together will Europeans be able to reduce the debt burden of everyone, get rid of the markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
Getting out of the crisis will require decisions at a pan-European level, and they cannot be made without full democratic legitimacy without leading us to disaster.
After a long discussion of this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone now demands a European economic government.
Let's do it.
But to imagine it without the stronger economic, political and democratic integration that has come into being is another madness and a new dead end.
We must start a new phase of European construction.
To establish a republic in France, it was necessary to "create" republicans.
A revolution of interests would not be enough.
