Contactless chip cards are spreading more and more widely.
The world’s first chip-card exhibition opens Tuesday in Vilpenté near Paris in an atmosphere of optimism.
In fact, 2011 will end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessors (bank cards, phones with SIM cards), surpassing, according to Eurosmart, 6 million units.
The most important sector is the contactless technology sector, which allows you to pay for public transport or purchases by simply carrying out a map of the reading device.
This year, the world will sell 460 million contactless chip cards compared to 320 million a year earlier!
Their share will increase in 2012 (expected 580 million units) and will account for almost 10% of the world market of chip cards (6,925 million cards).
Europe, long lagging behind the Asia-Pacific region, is now moving forward in the area of contactless payments.
About 26 million Visa bank cards are already equipped with this feature, and they are accepted by 75,000 terminals.
France is starting from a more modest position: there are 400,000 contactless Visa cards in circulation.
But large stores are increasing the pace.
This year, Carrefour released 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Passes.
In order to move to a higher speed, it is necessary for banks to supply their customers with equipment.
“Two large organizations in France have promised in the future to systematically distribute to their customers bank cards adapted for contactless use,” said Gerard Nebui, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks are testing payments using a mobile phone.
But this is only the first stage of the development of the future means of payment, that is, the mobile phone.
So far, only a few devices are equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary to carry out such transactions.
“They were postponed.
“But they really have to fly out next year.”
“We expect global sales of 80 to 120 million units in 2012,” explains Mark Berten, head of Eurosmart.
Banks are moving forward.
Yesterday, Crédit Agricole announced that it was conducting an experiment from December to June next year in Cannes.
The iPhone devices of about 200 customers and employees will be equipped with covers that provide contactless payments.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Société Générale also said yesterday that it is preparing to launch a market offering that allows its customers to pay via mobile phones.
The terrorist front is spreading from the Sahara to Nigeria
Paris is concerned about the links of the Islamic Maghreb with the Boko Haram sect.
Long-held links between the al-Qaida terrorist group in the Muslim Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian Boko Haram sect have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria’s Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even said that the Algerians are now certain of this.
“The way these two organizations are used and the intelligence reports show that they are actively cooperating,” he explained, without going into detail.
Paris seems to have drawn similar conclusions.
An investigation into the kidnapping of two French nationals in Niger in January found two links.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by people close to Aqmi, Antoine de Lecourt and Vincent Delori, apparently were killed the next day along with several of the kidnappers during an operation conducted by French special forces.
Among the debris left after the operation, French and Nigerian investigators found several phone SIM cards belonging to the terrorists.
Here's the terror
The analysis of the calls indicated several interlocutors who were in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two numbers; one points to a Nigerien who has long lived in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is a step forward, but we certainly need to wait for more reliable evidence before talking about the operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“It has been known for many years that the sect receives financial and ideological support from outside and that it is becoming more and more active,” says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, this support has become increasingly evident in the actions and statements of Boko Haram and its methods, which now include the use of suicide bombers and increasingly sophisticated explosive devices of the same type that Aqmi uses.
The international community, led by Washington, is now putting pressure on Abuja to draw attention there to the problems Boko Haram is creating.
The fact is that the Nigerian authorities have traditionally regarded this group as a community of enlightened people of no interest.
A quick success
Boko Haram, founded in 2002 in Maiduguri at a mosque, school and under the imam-fundamentalist Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means "Western education is a sin" - preaches the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the organization has achieved rapid success.
It is politicized and requires strict adherence to Sharia law, and its activists have begun to fight against the wicked central government.
It is aimed mainly at churches, bars and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active in carrying out numerous attacks on police stations.
Abuja's reaction, as usual, is uncompromising.
The army blockaded the city and left behind 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, taken alive, was killed in prison.
Now the sect is radicalizing and will go beyond its northern homelands.
Last Christmas, she took responsibility for the action that killed 80 people in Jose and then another in Abuja.
In June, in Abuja, Boko Haram organized the first suicide attack on a fortified police headquarters.
In August, the local office of the United Nations will become their first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which runs from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, is now of concern to all security experts.
Today, as Aqmi has strengthened in Mali and Niger, and Somalis from al-Shabaab are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram poses a new threat to the continent.
Last week, during a conversation with President Goodlak, Jonathan Allen Juppe warned of the dangers of Boko Haram and expressed his willingness to share all available information.
