Nord Stream, a new gateway for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The Nord Stream pipeline, connecting Western Europe and Russia directly at the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been launched.
It is designed to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between the performance of the orchestra and exquisite snacks, in the opening of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany under water.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rutte together turned the symbolic valve that controls the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
According to the new gas pipeline, 27.5 million additional cubic meters of gas will enter Western Europe every year on the first pipeline of 1,224 km, connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
The second pipeline should be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas equivalent to the total consumption of France.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
The Nord Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will become more difficult to influence Russia, threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop at the comparison of the Northern Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin with the aim of occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of supply.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of the direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already at an end.
“This pipeline is part of cooperation with Russia, it’s a new artery that organically connects us,” said Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon, opening the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the arrival point of gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel enclosed in concrete to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields left over from World War II.
“A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution,” said Jens Mueller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake with a weight equal to 242 Eiffel Towers, without gaps along its entire length, without valves and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers refused it, because Sweden was not delighted that the Russian state-owned company would permanently settle on its shores.
“In the event of an accident, we will cut off the gas flow in less than a minute,” says Jens Mueller.
So, in case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will go into the air.
But this seems unlikely to the designers who designed the seams, designed for leakage only once every 100,000 years.
Control of the condition of the gas pipeline will be carried out by an underwater robot, which pulls the ship, for external monitoring, as well as by the apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
The cigarette-shaped apparatus is inserted into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and pushed forward by the flow of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it gives accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
The circulation of gas is carried out only by means of its pressure.
It is 200 bar upon departure and 100 bar upon arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement the project.
The leader is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was tasked with building and operating a gas pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Then Gazprom leased this company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the full amount, no matter how much gas is actually transported,” says Jens Mueller.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 thousand million euros for two pipelines.
GDF Suez’s investment will be about 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay back their costs, because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The pipeline exits the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy shore, planted with coniferous trees.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the output terminal of the gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 it will be 6 million.
Moleskine brand notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company fifteen years ago, will return the taste to the letter.
It has the aroma of adventures, hours spent writing in candlelight.
Moleskine block is easy to recognize by a rectangular black cover, by rubber, by yellowish-white pages, as if yellowing with time.
However, Moleskine’s notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, located in Milan, has decided to launch design notebooks for sale.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, took responsibility for launching the new product.
The block is inspired by the old production technique, Moleskine - lacquered cotton cloth, which was used, for example, to cover the stools.
It is claimed that this type of notebook is highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has brought into line with today’s taste an old and forgotten thing that was a cult for avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the managing brand at Modo Modo.
Success has come.
From 2006 to 2010, sales increased by 25% and reached 12.7 million units.
We went far from the production of the first years, when only 3000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish the profile of a typical buyer, because the notebook equally attracts a businessman, a student and a person of free profession.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, have broad views and educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notes in bookstores Fnac, shops in the centers of small cities and was able to acquire widespread fame.
“We followed the spirit of the times and this new need for writing, despite the advent of e-mail,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This characteristic cultural feature accompanies the development of Moleskine; the brand recently organized the exhibition “The Surrounding Path”, where architects and artists demonstrated their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched a cover with a leopard print on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Leveraging its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags. The brand includes all kinds of support.
In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which has entered a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for people with disabilities begins today.
Despite a public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate among people with disabilities is still twice the average, 19% versus 9% for the general population.
Disheartening?
“No,” said Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for people with disabilities.
“In 15 years, we have made significant progress.”
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not at two, but three times higher.”
“But there’s still a lot of work ahead.”
It must be said that there are still many obstacles to employment for the disabled.
Among them, 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They are more likely to have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education only 10,000 people with disabilities.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for people with disabilities versus 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are the essence of the problem,” said Christian Grappen, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire people with disabilities.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association commissioned by Cité found that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and “represented people who were completely in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally deficient.”
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6% of workers with disabilities set out in a law passed in 1987.
The last known figures for 2008 are 2.6%.
“Today we are about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for tax collection from companies that do not comply with the law.
Proof: The number of "taxed" organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which raised the tax, put a lot of pressure on the company,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects an increase in awareness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have employees with disabilities, compared to 82% of organizations with 100 to 199 employees.
